column11: Please copy the urls from all the products that you used. (Separated by a comma)
column17: comments
Does airport mean KOGD?  Or could it be U42?  Persistence method today for the forecast through Wednesday.
Do you want us to say that writing down numbers for forecasting for SLC as Big picture or normal forecast location?  That takes up a major of my 38 minutes today, was just writing down info.
High and lows already happened for BTF and OGD on day 1.
Ridging after this storm was why so few models were used today.
NCEP Model guidance was using both GFS and NAM HIRES.
Complex forecast today, caused an exceedingly long time on the normal forecast location.  Even brought the Canadian down for the party today.
Persistence method was used  for most of the forecast.
Unsure about day 2 high.
Easy forecast due to #Ruffleshaverrrriiiiiidddddgggeeesss
Took 25 minutes on normal forecast location time.
22 Minutes to do Local location.  Today has less links because the 3 day forecast is not very complex.
Please fix spelling errors.
Easy forecast due to massive ridge.

It took me about 40 minutes to do my normal forecast and another 10 minutes to forecast for Ogden so I don't think the part where you choose how much time you spent on Big Picture and Normal Forecast Location is very reflective of how much time was spent. I think it would be easier if we just put in the number like 40 minutes or something.
Overall it took me 45 minutes to do the entire forecast including the new area. It took me about 20 minutes to do the normal forecast location instead of 15.
I really liked the SREF plumes that you introduced they were very helpful. I have noticed that there are a few spelling errors though so you guys may want to go through and double check those.
I was confident for today's forecast. The next few days there could be some rain so I'm slightly less confident but we'll see what happens.

I just realized that in the links I posted from last week that the dates hadn't been updated (because I put them all in a spreadsheet and would just add links or take them out when I didn't use them). So some of the dates might be off, but the product is the same. Just letting you know.

column17: The total forecast took 1 hour and 20 minutes. Most of the forecasters in this office take about 1 hour to complete their normal forecasts. Since the sliders above could not represent my actual times, here they are listed below. / -Big Picture Status / Overview ~ 20 mins / -Normal Forecast Location ~ 40 mins / -Additional Forecast Location ~ 20 mins /  / Additionally, I did not do completely separate forecasts for each location. Rather, I took the data for both locations at the same time. In all, forecasting for the additional location did take about 20 mins.  /  / NOTE: A few minor typos on the page in the "How confident were you in your forecasts?" section.
My forecast took 1 hour and 23 minutes, but the sliders could not fully represent this time. Here are the detailed times: / Overview-11 mins / Normal Forecast~40 mins / Extra Location~32 mins

column17: The time that I spent on the big picture was closer to 35 minutes, and the normal forecast location was another 20.
Total time for big picture 15:35,  additional time for local forecast: 34:05.
Big picture: 27 minutes / Normal Forecast Location: 33 minutes
An unseasonable cold front is moving through today, making me a bit less confident with my forecasts.
I was not able to use the SREF plumes that you provided for today. The link worked, but the model didn't appear to have run.
Only somewhat confident for KOGD because of huge uncertainty on Sunday between models.
Lower confidence due to rain expected on Friday and Saturday.
Lower confidence due to rain.
Took slightly longer than 15 minutes to look at big picture and local forecasts
